## 1. Array Memory Layout & Addressing Mathematics
An **Array** is a collection of homogeneous elements allocated in **contiguous memory blocks**. The base address of the array is denoted as `Base(A)`. For a 1D array where each element size is `W` bytes, the memory address of the element at index `i` is calculated using the formula:

$$\text{Address}(A[i]) = \text{Base}(A) + i \times W$$

### Multi-dimensional Array Mapping
For a 2D array of dimensions $M \times N$, elements are linearized in memory using one of two schemes:
1. **Row-Major Order (RMO)**: Row by row. Address of $A[i][j]$ is:
   $$\text{Address}(A[i][j]) = \text{Base}(A) + (i \times N + j) \times W$$
2. **Column-Major Order (CMO)**: Column by column. Address of $A[i][j]$ is:
   $$\text{Address}(A[i][j]) = \text{Base}(A) + (j \times M + i) \times W$$

