## 3. Two Pointers Technique
The **Two Pointers** pattern uses two references (typically pointing to the start and end of a sorted array) to slide towards each other, reducing nesting loops from $O(n^2)$ to $O(n)$.

**Common Scenario (Target Sum)**: Find if two elements in a sorted array add up to a target sum.
```javascript
function hasTargetSum(arr, target) {
  let left = 0;
  let right = arr.length - 1;

  while (left < right) {
    const currentSum = arr[left] + arr[right];
    if (currentSum === target) return true;
    if (currentSum < target) {
      left++; // Increase sum by shifting left pointer right
    } else {
      right--; // Decrease sum by shifting right pointer left
    } 
  }
  return false;
}
```

---

## 4. Key Takeaways
- Contiguous arrays offer $O(1)$ index lookups but $O(n)$ shifts on middle insertions.
- **Kadane's Algorithm** is the optimal $O(n)$ solver for maximum subarray sums.
- **Two Pointers** is the standard mechanism to optimize sorted array searches.

